Sep 18 2009 	Great place to stay in Las Vegas	Stayed at the Mandalay Bay for 4 nights to attend a conference and spend some free time to play. This was the perfect place to stay as they had many options for meals and night life. Didn't get to use the pool, however, the spa was wonderful! The shopping was great as well as the service in the hotel and the casino. Can't wait to go back in December 2009! Keep up the great work Mandalay Bay!	
Sep 17 2009 	Best. Hotel Pool. Ever.	The Mandalay Bay Beach is why you want to go here. It is outstanding. Bodysurfing in the wave pool is so much fun! The lazy river is very fast and is fun to just float on by holding your breath - which is good, because there are no tubes available. You have to buy them at $25 for adults or $16 for kids. My advice - get some cheap ones before you come to town. Still, you can enjoy yourself without a float. If you're lucky, you might even find a chair on the beach, if you try hard enough. I always got the strange sensation that there were more towels holding empty chairs than there were people in the pools, but on the upside, the pools never felt crowded. Despite these complaints, the beach was outstanding and is a huge reason to stay at the Bay.We had a 750DR suite and loved it, it was a fantastic room. The bed was extremely comfortable, and the bathroom was nothing short of luxurious. And being upstairs from all the restaurants located on site was a nice perk, especially the in-room guide notifying guests of the excellent and better-than-expected happy hour specials, such as $7 drinks at rumjungle that some with free appetizers. (Hey, they're normally $13 drinks, and they're amazing, so I'll take what I can get.)There were only two downsides to my stay at Mandalay. First, it was LOUD, in that I could hear everybody making a racket in the hallway at all hours of the night. I can't say if that was just a fluke and we had rude, noisy neighbors, or if for all the effort they put into a luxury suite that they went cheap on the door to the room. Whatever, that's a minor complaint, just odd for such a great hotel.The second downside is the location. If you know the Strip, you know that the Mandalay is the furthest hotel away on the south end of the Strip. I'm used to walking the Strip, but it really takes a long time to walk from the Mandalay just out to NYNY and MGM. Luckily, the express tram from the hotel to that very intersection is extremely handy for this. Having a car, and the free parking in Vegas, also helped. Still, I wouldn't recommend staying here for your first time in Vegas. Stay somewhere centrally located so you can more easily access the Strip. Then when you're ready to come back and enjoy a spectacular pool, look no further than the Mandalay Bay.	
