Jul 30 2009 	A Great Place to Stay in Las Vegas	My girlfriend and I stayed in Mandalay bay from July 21-25, 2009. I received an email promotion for two free nights through the players club (and I'm not a high roller or anything like that). The other two nights were 80, so it was a deal I could not pass up.We stayed on the sixth floor of the main hotel (not THEHotel) in a non-smoking king room. The room was very clean and well-apportioned. The bathroom is giant, and the free toiletries were quite good (I was thrilled that they give you a sewing kit!). There is a TV in the bathroom, and I actually decided to take a bath so I could try it out. The bed is top-notch, somewhere between a Marriott and a Westin in terms of comfort, and that's saying something. The main television is as good as you will find in Vegas. It actually had a lot of channels, many in HD, which is rare for Vegas. Of course, there are no coffee makers in the room, but if you go to Vegas for free coffee in your hotel room then you need to reevaluate your reasons for going there in the first place. Housecleaning was very good, although if you forgot to put a sign on the door, they would knock at like 8:45-9:00 AM, which is a little early in Vegas time. Beware of the microfridge, there are sensors in there that will charge you if you pull something out. That being said, my girlfriend pulled out a snickers bar to look at it (insert eye-roll here), then put it back, but I wasn't charged for it.A cabbie told me that the hotel had laid off 70% of its workers, and I believe it. While I did not experience and big problems, you could tell that they could have had more people working at check in/ check out, and there was only one bell hop working to retrieve checked bags when we left. That being said, all the staff I encountered was extremely friendly and helpful. This is the kind of service I would expect at a four or five star hotel.A lot of people have complained about the hotel elevators on this sight. Maybe it's because they stayed on a higher floor, or were in THEHotel, but we experienced very few problems. I suppose that because people take the elevator to the pool that this increases traffic. Sometimes we had to wait because elevators were full, but we never had to wait more than a minute or two to get from point A to B.The pool is amazing. I'm sure that I can't say much more than has already been said about it here. We went on a Wednesday morning at around 10:30 AM, and it was very crowded, but since it was over 100 outside we stayed in one of the smaller pools for almost an hour. I do not advocate taking children to Las Vegas, but if you do, the pool area here is a great attraction.We only ate at two restaurants in the Hotel: The Burger Bar and Canter's Deli. The Burger bar is really great, and considering the popularity of such restaurants these days, this is saying something. They also have Dog Fish Head beer on tap, which is a plus. Canter's deli is a little window next to their excellent sports book. Great deli food, with sandwiches that are big enough to share for two people. The casino, like similar MGM properties, is not particularly special. However, it is one of the roomiest casino floors I have ever seen, and if you are a slot player, this is a good place for you. Not the best drink service on the floor, however. I like to play lower minimums, so I didn't hit the tables here that much, although there were five dollar craps tables most mornings that I was there.The location is at the end of the strip, so you should plan on taking a lot of cabs, especially if it is hot. We took the tram to Excalibur once, and I didn't think it was worth the wait or hassle. There are a lot of older people on the tram who act like they've never been on a train before, which is a little frustrating. Of course, if you have mobility issues, this is a good way to get you moving up the strip.I live in Connecticut, so I don't make it out to Vegas more than once a year. I would put Mandalay bay on par with Caesars in most respects (better rooms at Mandalay, better shopping/food at Caesars). I would also say that it is a suitable alternative to the Bellagio, especially if you are a closet cheapo like me and you get such a good bargain. That being said, if I was forced to pay over 250 per night to stay at Mandalay Bay, you'd probably find me at the Flamingo. Overall, I would highly recommend this hotel.	
