Jun 12 2009 	BEST BEDS EVER	we took our teenager and her friend, we booked a two bed room suite and it was worth it. it was a little pricey but the 5 tv's and both bathrooms having a jacuzzi tub was amazing. they said it was a strip view but we were looking the wrong way down the strip, and had a perfect view of the airport nearby. there was a 1/4 view of the good strip right behind a piller in the room. The pools were great but very crowded and bring your own tubes to go on the lazy river or they will charge you 23.99 for a tube... there is no &quot;renting&quot; them as the site says there is. but were still a lot of fun. Now about the food... I went here six months ago and the buffet was the best in las vegas but after this weekend I would almost say it was the worst. the selection is the same at noon as it is at 6pm. the quality seemed to have gone down quite a bit. the noodle place was awesome the teens said. all in all a great family trip, and I have never had a better night sleep in a hotel in my life. and if you are going to go to the aquarium go there before you go to the buffet... they have a special price to add dinner and it save like 10 bucks per person. we also saved a ton of money by bringing a ice chest and suitcase filled with snack food and drinks. sodas from the mini bar cost 4 bucks and the display on the counter is weight and item sensitive so when my teen first walked in and saw that they put out cookies for us she didn't get that that little pack of tiny cookies was $8.62. also make sure if you are going to gamble at all to get a player card, they comped 2 breakfast bufftets for me after only like 4 hours of play.	
Jun 12 2009 	Gorgeous hotel - look no further (but prepare to spend lots of money)	Our first stay at Mandalay Bay more than exceeded our expectations. From the moment we stepped into the lobby to check in, we were very impressed by the understated elegance of the decor, the immaculate cleanliness, and the delicate fragrance pumped through the ventilation system. We checked in at around noon on a Wednesday, and contrary to some other reviews, we had no wait at all. When we got to our room, we were further impressed that although we were in a (requested) smoking section, the corridors and room itself did not smell of smoke, but rather, the corridor was fragranced as was the lobby. The room itself was impeccably clean. We found one light bulb not working and no ashtrays in the room; we called the front desk, and housekeeping arrived within minutes to replace the bulb and give us ashtrays - great service. The bed was comfy, with a pillow-top mattress, and I was delighted to find an iPod dock alarm clock and a good hair dryer NOT bolted to the wall as in some other hotels. Our only minor quibble was that the double-sink counter tops were a little too high to reach comfortably (we're both around 5'4&quot;), but we managed. Even the toiletries provided (shampoo, conditioner, body lotion, glycerin facial soap, and oatmeal bath soap) were first-rate. The decor of the room, as with the public areas, was quite pleasing, done in subtle earth tones, and lacking any of the over-the-top gaudiness of some of the other area hotels.We ate at the Bayside Buffet, Raffles Cafe, the Burger Bar, and THEcafe at THEhotel, and enjoyed them all. The buffet was the best quality of any we've ever had, with really well-prepared dishes; not a huge selection as at some buffets, but also unlike many or most buffets, the food was really good: quality over quantity seemed to be the key here. Pricey, yes, but you get what you pay for. Be prepared to spend a lot on food if you eat here: we had breakfast at Raffles one day, two diners: one waffle, one order of coconut pancakes, a la carte bacon, orange juice (a huge 16-oz, glass vs. the usual 4 to 6 ounces elsewhere), and coffee for both: about $60 with the tip. Absolutely delicious, but yes, expensive. Had a late night dinner at THEcafe: 2 club sandwiches and soft drinks, about $36 with tip. But terrific food: if you want cheap vs. high quality, go elsewhere. The ambiance at all the restaurants we tried (except for Burger Bar, which was rather ordinary-looking, like a typical New York burger joint) was wonderful. The Bayside Buffet was a lovely room, NOT like the usual cafeteria style of other buffets: we felt we were dining in a restaurant, with the tables far enough away from the serving areas to be quiet and relaxing. THEcafe is one of the most lovely dining rooms I've ever experienced, with quietly elegant black, silver, and cream furnishings, and relaxing, ethereal music piped in.The Beach, the hotel's pool area, was fabulously beautiful, but crowded - neither of us wanted to spend time laying around in the sun, but if we did, we noticed it would have been difficult to find lounge chairs, and this was mid-week. It was quieter and more relaxing than some others, though, with no loud music We explored other hotels in this price range while in LV: Bellagio, the Mirage, Planet Hollywood, etc., but felt Mandalay Bay was the most beautiful of all of them. We would absolutely stay again.	
