Apr 22 2009 	Spacious Room and a Bonus Too!	We spent three nights at Mandalay Bay and I chose this hotel based on the pool. My husband was attending a conference and we are not big gamblers so the pool was the factor. We’ve had a long cold winter in Seattle and needed some fun in the sun. Check-in went smoothly and our room was perfect for us. 31st floor with a view of the pools. Our king bed was super comfy – just like at home, two closets – just like at home, and a great bathroom with soaking tub, separate shower and TV – wish I had that at home. My husband would have appreciated a coffee maker. Yes, the elevators are inconsistent and the response from the staff was “our elevators have a mind of their own.” The Pools – there are several pools in the complex including a wave pool and lazy river. People were lining up before the pools opened in the morning and you are hard pressed to find a lounge chair after the first couple of hours. Although there are signs saying you can’t ‘reserve’ chairs, it is very common to see towels laid out on a chair and nobody in sight for the majority of the day. This is so inconsiderate to those of us who actually want to use pool chairs. Families seem to gather near the wave pool and lazy river and it’s quieter at the outlying pools. We have an awesome wave pool at a water park in Seattle and I was disappointed by the Mandalay Bay wave pool. One wave every three minutes or so. Boring. But the lazy river was fun – quick current and a good length. Next time I would bring my own inflatable float – the hotel charges $16 to purchase one and no rentals are available. You can order basic grill items at $10 a pop and drinks are about the same. We found the Border Grill right outside of the pool area to have good food and interesting drinks. I loved the Baha Ceviche. We rented a pool cabana one day and it was really fun to have that extra pampering and extra shade. The temperature went up to 92 degrees and we were able to duck inside and take a break from the sun. The cabana included a comfy couch, fridge including six complimentary soft drinks and six small bottles of water, a bucket of ice, a giant TV which we didn’t use at all, a table with two chairs, and two lounge chairs outside with a small table to set books and drinks on. The cabana also included two floats for the pools. Waiters checked on us throughout the day for food and drink requests which went on a separate tab. My husband was able to finish up some work on his laptop in the cabana while I read outside. It was a great day. Restaurants – we had one breakfast at the buffet and it was average – fruit, meats, omelets to order. Nothing especially innovative. We ate twice at Raffles, only because it was the only place open when we were hungry. It was very average and overpriced. There is a Subway sandwich shop across the street and a small grocery store. We picked up a bottle of wine and used the corkscrew and wine glasses provided in our room.Location -- We didn’t mind the end of the strip location. We took the tram to Excaliber, Luxor and walked across the street to NYNY and MGM. We took cabs to evening events at other hotels.	
Apr 22 2009 	Mandalay Bay with the family	We spent 6 days at Mandalay Bay in mid-April to celebrate our 25th anniversary. We picked Mandalay Bay for two reasons - the availability of a 2 bedroom suite with 2 beds in it (for our 14 year old daughter and 13 year old son) and the pools.Check in took a little while. Rather than one line where you go to the next available window, there were multiple lines (one line for each clerk) so you could be stuck in a slow line. We had requested a non-smoking two bedroom suite with two beds in the 2nd room. When we got to our room, it was obvious that the previous quests had been smokers and there was just a king in the 2nd bedroom. A call to the front desk got us moved to the proper room but after a comment from them that they don't guarantee a particular configuration in the suites (that despite having a confirmation from my travel agency for 2 beds in the 2nd room.Plasma TVs in each bedroom and the living room area along with smaller LCD TV's in each bathroom. Our bathroom had a large Jacuzzi tub and the 2nd bathroom had a huge shower complete with a rain shower head in the ceiling.The suite was very roomy and comfortable with many amenities but a microwave or coffee maker would have been nice.There are many food options but all high priced. We walked to the Luxor and took advantage of their lower priced food court (Quiznos, McDonalds, etc). The BBQ pork sandwich at the House of Blues was very good.Yes it is located at the southern end of the strip and it's a distance to many other places but we knew this ahead of time so we can't complain about that.The pools are very nice but extremely crowded. They tout having a sand beach but it's wall to wall lounge chairs. On a nice day if you don't get there first thing in the morning you will not get a chair.We're not big gamblers but we found the casino to be one of the most appealing of those we visited. There is plenty of open space between groups of machines and the ceiling is higher than in many other casinos. That gives it a more open and airy feel than others we saw (Harrah's for example, gave us claustrophobia &lt;g&gt;).The concierge was very helpful and pleasant, booking us for a day trip to Hoover Dam.Overall a pleasant experience and we'd consider Mandalay Bay should we return to Vegas.	
